I didn't need to run "autoreconf; automake; ./configure; make" twice.
Anyway, I don't think we may fix this Makefile circular dependancies hell.

  * autoreconf is a script manipulating aclocal + autoconf + autoheader
  * aclocal produces aclocal.m4 from acinclude.m4
  * automake produces Makefile.in files from Makefile.am files
  * autoconf produces configure from configure.in and aclocal.m4
  * autoheader produces config.h.in from configure.in
  * configure produces Makefile files from Makefile.in files
  * configure produces config.h from config.h.in
  * configure produces executable config.status to rebuild files from *.in
  * config.status --recheck regenerates itself from configure
  * make _should_ run everything above automatically using Makefile

Now you may guess what happens when Makefile itself should be regenerated
when you issue "make foobar". I.e. it should first produce a new Makefile
instead of the currently run one, and then rerun "make foobar" on it.

Regards,
Mikhael.
